DIV2.P:
4. Although the love which Christ manifested in his death, is undoubt∣edly included in his Righteousness, and is the most eminent instance of it;


yet we cannot think that this was all he intended, when he said he came to fulfil every jot and tittle of the law. This expression evidently includes, not only the "weightier matters of the law," such as perfect love to God and man; but also all "the least of those commandments," wherein that love should be expressed. And we find that the Righteousness of Christ does in fact answer to the most minute, as well as the most important duties of the law. It is universal, and in every respect perfect. Neither the greatest nor the least precept was neglected by him. He laid down his life for his brethren, in obedience to the high command of his Father, and he was subject to Joseph and Mary,Luke, 2. 51. in con∣formity to the fifth precept of the law. And it should be observed that he did


all this because it was easier for heaven and earth to pass away, than for one tittle of the law to fail.
